To assess the selectivity of the N-CDs sensor for metal ions, the fluorescence quenching effect of different metal ions on N-CDs was investigated (Fig. 6
                        ). As displayed in Fig. 6A, a significant fluorescence quenching effect was observed upon addition of Cr(VI) ions, while the other metal ions (Fig. 6A) exhibited negligible or less quenching effect. Furthermore, as shown in Fig. 6B, the coexistence of Cr(VI) ions with mixture of metal ions had little effect on the fluorescence quenching. These findings reveal that the obtained N-CDs are only sensitive to Cr(VI) in the mixtures but insensitive to the other metal ions. The comparison between the present study and the some recent reported on sensing of metal ions is summarized Table 1
                        . As can be seen, in this study, the N-doped carbon dots can be convenient prepared through a lower temperature and shorter time reaction process. In addition, our N-doped carbon dots (N-CDs) showed good fluorescence sensing for Cr(VI) with high selectivity.
